&gt;
Pages such as this one, 
http://sig.biostr.washington.edu/share/docs/cvs/cvs_50.html, would warn 
us away from doing such a thing though it looks like we could do it.

I&#39;d think we&#39;d more likely do this pointing-at-current-(stable)-version 
using signifiers on our downloads page rather than with labels in CVS.

St.Ack

&gt;on our downloads page rather than with tags in cvs.
&gt;  
&gt;
&gt;- Gordon
&gt;
&gt;Michael Stack wrote:
&gt;  
&gt;
&gt;&gt;1. Let the crawler versioning scheme be MAJOR.MINOR.POINT_VERSION w/ 
&gt;&gt;qualifier of &#39;-dev&#39; while building toward &#39;stable&#39; versions. Examples 
&gt;&gt;would be 0.1.1-dev, 1.0.23, 2.0.1, etc. 
&gt;&gt;2. Let our first release be 0.1.0. 
&gt;&gt;3. Let increments to MAJOR or MINOR merit branching. Let the branch be 
&gt;&gt;named MAJOR.MINOR (I think &#39;.&#39; is disallowed so will have to be 
&gt;&gt;MAJOR_MINOR).
&gt;&gt;4. Releases made along a branch should only ever be bug fixes and should 
&gt;&gt;only ever increment POINT_VERSION. Such releases should be tagged 
&gt;&gt;MAJOR.MINOR.POINT_VERSION (Keeping this scheme, we&#39;ll be able to easily 
&gt;&gt;distingush branches and tags looking at cvs logs).  
&gt;&gt;5. Adding significant functionality should merit an increment to MINOR 
&gt;&gt;number while a suite of new functionality would merit an increase in 
&gt;&gt;MAJOR numbering (This last bullet item is pretty nebulous.  I think 
&gt;&gt;it&#39;ll just be &quot;obvious&quot; when its time to roll the MAJOR rather than MINOR).
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;St.Ack
